MAPPED TYPES create new types by iterating over the keys of an existing type:

```typescript
// Make all properties optional
type Partial<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] };

// Make all properties readonly
type Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] };

// Transform value types
type Stringify<T> = { [K in keyof T]: string };

// Modify only specific keys
type Nullable<T> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null };
```

You can also add or remove modifiers:
```typescript
// Remove readonly and optional
type Mutable<T> = { -readonly [K in keyof T]-?: T[K] };
```

Mapped types are the foundation of most utility types (`Partial`, `Required`, `Readonly`, `Pick`, `Omit`, `Record`).

TEMPLATE LITERAL TYPES combine string literal types using backtick syntax, similar to JavaScript template literals but at the TYPE level:

```typescript
type EventName = 'click' | 'focus' | 'blur';
type Handler = `on${Capitalize<EventName>}`;  // 'onClick' | 'onFocus' | 'onBlur'

type PropSetter<T extends string> = `set${Capitalize<T>}`;
type A = PropSetter<'name'>; // 'setName'

// Generating event handler types automatically:
type DOMHandlers = { [E in EventName as `on${Capitalize<E>}`]: (e: Event) => void };
// { onClick: ...; onFocus: ...; onBlur: ... }
```

Built-in type manipulation helpers: `Uppercase`, `Lowercase`, `Capitalize`, `Uncapitalize`.

Powerful for generating typed APIs from string literal unions (e.g. CSS property names, event handler names, query builders).

`infer` introduces a TYPE VARIABLE that TypeScript fills in when the pattern matches:

```typescript
// Extract element type from an array
type ElementType<T> = T extends (infer E)[] ? E : never;
type N = ElementType<number[]>;           // number
type S = ElementType<string[]>;           // string
type X = ElementType<boolean>;            // never (not an array)

// Extract first argument type
type FirstArg<T> = T extends (arg: infer A, ...args: any[]) => any ? A : never;
type F = FirstArg<(a: string, b: number) => void>; // string

// Extract Promise value
type Awaited<T> = T extends Promise<infer V> ? Awaited<V> : T;
```

`infer` works by structural pattern matching — TypeScript tries to match the checked type against the pattern and binds the inferred position to the variable. Multiple `infer` in the same type are all independent.
